name: 4-(4-(Dimethylamino)benzylidene)-2-phenyl-1,3-oxazol-5(4H)-one
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-3877
Reason: The target compound has several functional groups that influence its melting point. The basic unit here is the 1,3-oxazol-5(4H)-one ring system. Phenyl rings usually have a melting point in the region of 80 degrees Celsius, serving as a starting point. The oxazole ring introduces nitrogen and oxygen heteroatoms, which can significantly increase the melting point through improved resonance stabilization and hydrogen bonding potential (+50 degrees Celsius). The substitution of the phenyl ring at the para position with a dimethylamino group introduces steric bulk and can donate electron density via mesomeric effects, slightly raising the melting point (+10 degrees Celsius). The benzylidene linker (∼C=C-) has the potential to introduce rigidity due to the double bond, which would also lead to a higher melting point (+15 degrees Celsius). Combining these effects, we derive an estimated melting point for the compound.
